title: For Sale:  Colt 1851 Navy .36 caliber revolver with Hartford Address Barrel(C13680)
postcontent: Colt 1851 Navy .36 caliber revolver with Hartford Address Barrel. This is a gunsmith conversion of a percussion Colt, after the Civil War. The action works fine and visible serial numbers are matching. This is an uncleaned near relic condition revolver. We have commented before on the collectible aspect of relic guns, and our opinion that these guns have an attraction and charm of their own. How and where did the gun come from? What could have happened to it to arrive at this condition? The revolver has not only that “relic” appeal but is a collectible example of the gunsmith’s work. He cut the cylinder where the nipples go and welded in a “conversion plate”. Using the original percussion hammer, he reshaped the nose into a conical, almost nail like projection, to strike a rimfire cartridge. This is crude work, but you can’t help but smile in wonder at the creativeness or lack thereof. If you buy it please don’t clean it. Mother nature’s work (rush and corrosion) should be left alone in this case.http://www.collectorsfirearms.com/colt-1851-navy-36-caliber-revolver-with-hartford-address-barrel-c13680/

title: For Sale/Trade:  SIG P365, LNIB with factory box, 2 magazines
location: RTP, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
The only way to get one of these is to be on a waiting list and be patient, or to buy one from someone who was on a waiting list.I was on two different waiting lists and ended up with two of these guns. I only need one.The gun is great. Slightly larger than a P938, easily pocket-carried in my pants pocket. Standard capacity is 10, so, you can carry it at 10+1 with your choice of 9mm rounds (I use HST). The gun is rated for +P. It has SIGLite night sights installed by the factory. It has no manual safety.I have closely compared this gun with a P938 and with a Kimber Solo, both of which are 6+1 pocket 9mm pistols. The 365 is a little bigger, but not that much. All three guns fit in my pocket just fine. The 365 is significantly smaller than a Shield.The gun comes with two magazines. One fits flush and is my preference for pocket carry. The other has a pinky extension and would be better for the range, or if you have room for it however you carry. SIG also sells a 12-round magazine for about $45.I've shot this particular gun enough to say it's weirdly accurate ... more accurate than makes sense to me. The sights are great. The trigger is great. SIG is onto something special with this model.
I paid $568 and change for the gun at Bass Pro, including tax. I paid about $20 for a BORAII holster, which I will include. Price shown is for a cash sale. $590 is approximately what I have in the gun and holster. Price is firm. If you can get it cheaper somewhere else, go for it. Trade value - $650.
